	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			<div>
				Originally Posted by <strong>Dramadon</strong>
				
			</div>
			<div class="message">I think you've missed the point of what the message in the game is. You keep searching for some higher moral statement that this game could be making. It doesn't. It just shows realistic responses to an apocalyptic world where people are pretty much on their own for their own survival (mixed in with the unrealistic reality of a video game where one or two people kill dozens of others with guns to progress). If you don't think that the ending that happened is completely out of the realm of what human beings would do, then you need to observe human nature a bit more. How many couples live with a lie to keep their marriage together? How many times do people willingly ignore things just to maintain a relationship? When Ellie accepts Joel's answer, she is making the choice to live with the lie. 10 years from now she may feel differently, but not at this moment.</div>
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div>If it's honestly Ellie's choice to give up, then they need to <i>show</i> that. My point isn't that it's unrealistic for people to make shitty choices, it's that there is NO FOUNDATION for the choices made by the characters in the end game. Especially when it comes to Ellie. And while real life can be dull and meander without point, I think it fairly obvious that stories that are dull and meander without point are just poorly written. Again, there are a lot of directions they could have gone with the ending and made me happy, but they chose none of them, and it just kind of meandered to a close. If you were going to do that, why not just make the game about Joel and Ellie and get rid of all this &quot;save the world&quot; nonsense in the first place?<br />
<br />
As someone who wants to make a living telling stories, then I have to flat disagree with you that a confusing ending is okay; you can embolden a reader, you can drive them to despair, you can leave them with a hollow emptiness of guilt or wracked with fear. But to just leave them confused as to what happened? That's flat out piss poor storytelling, and it means you did something wrong. The fact that that sort of ending gets hailed as Awesome is a strong indicator that storytelling in games as a whole has gotten pretty staid and tired, absolutely. There's just danger in telling developers that it's okay to make crappy endings just because they're new and different.<br />
<br />
I could make a fairly easy comparison between Last of Us and Mass Effect 3, honestly. Both games left me restless and vaguely frustrated after the ending, but the feelings had everything to do with a story left unfinished and shot full of holes than that feeling being the actual point of the writers. The difference is that the gaming community rose up against ME3's ending and (correctly) labeled it as poor quality, whereas Last of Us receives full marks. The difference in reaction has everything to do with the type of game; ME3 is full of player choices and so the players feel cheated by a cop-out ending. Last of Us has no choice whatsoever and so players don't feel cheated, they just shrug and accept things at face value because they don't have a say in the matter.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
