	</div>
</div>&quot;Daring&quot; would be making the flat statement that it's totally okay to kill one person in the name of saving humanity (How many shows/movies/games push that sort of message? A scant handful?). Daring might also be saying that &quot;Yes, Joel is a selfish bastard for doing this but that's life, sucks to be human.&quot; I would call the ending of Last of Us different, but I wouldn't call it daring. Or perhaps it is daring in the same way that the art installation which is a competent study canvas slashed into strips is, because it is &quot;edgy&quot; or whatever. Again, I don't -want- the standard pleasure of a happy ending. I want the cold wrench of despair at having to lose this child who you have shepherded through this entire game, the anger and deep sadness of grief that her life is cut short, contrasted against the stark reality of the situation. That's not happy, nor is it pleasurable, and Joel can either accept the choice or be broken upon it. The fact that they wasted the potential of the setup they created is what bothers me the most.</blockquote>
